<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910503-0030</DOCNO><DOCID>910503-0030.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Affiliated Publications   Says it May Buy Out   Boston Globe Managers</HL><DATE>05/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   AFP</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>MASSACHUSETTS (MA)</RE><LP>   BOSTON -- Affiliated Publications Inc., publisher of theBoston Globe, disclosed that it may seek to buy out someGlobe management positions to cut costs.   Like many newspapers, the Globe has had lower advertisingrevenue in recent years. Last month, Affiliated reported afirst-quarter loss of $993,000, or one cent a share, onrevenue of $128.6 million, the first quarterly loss in itshistory.</LP><TEXT>   Affiliated earlier disclosed that the Globe has started anattrition program to cut 100 white-collar jobs over the nextfive years. This week, Globe publisher William O. Taylor toldthe newspaper's employees that the attrition program won't beenough to &quot;cope&quot; with the New England recession's effects onthe paper, said Richard Gulla, an Affiliated spokesman.   Further cost-cutting measures, including possible buy-outsof Globe managers, are &quot;options that are being considered,&quot;Mr. Gulla added. &quot;There's no buy-out plan, or wage-freeze orother plan on the table specifically. No layoffs arescheduled, and layoffs haven't been put into any plans wehave.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>